Happy 2026! Will this be the year we finally achieve AGI? I‚Äôd like to propose a new version of the Turing Test, which I‚Äôll call the Turing-AGI Test, to see if we‚Äôve achieved this. I‚Äôll explain in a moment why having a new test is important.

The public thinks achieving AGI means computers will be as intelligent as people and be able to do most or all knowledge work. I‚Äôd like to propose a new test. The test subject ‚Äî either a computer or a skilled professional human ‚Äî is given access to a computer that has internet access and software such as a web browser and Zoom. The judge will design a multi-day experience for the test subject, mediated through the computer, to carry out work tasks. For example, an experience might consist of a period of training (say, as a call center operator), followed by being asked to carry out the task (taking calls), with ongoing feedback. This mirrors what a remote worker with a fully working computer (but no webcam) might be expected to do.

A computer passes the Turing-AGI Test if it can carry out the work task as well as a skilled human.

Most members of the public likely believe a real AGI system will pass this test. Surely, if computers are as intelligent as humans, they should be able to perform work tasks as well as a human one might hire. Thus, the Turing-AGI Test aligns with the popular notion of what AGI means.

Here‚Äôs why we need a new test: ‚ÄúAGI‚Äù has turned into a term of hype rather than a term with a precise meaning. A reasonable definition of AGI is AI that can do any intellectual task that a human can. When businesses hype up that they might achieve AGI within a few quarters, they usually try to justify these statements by setting a much lower bar. This mismatch in definitions is harmful because it makes people think AI is becoming more powerful than it actually is. I‚Äôm seeing this mislead everyone from high-school students (who avoid certain fields of study because they think it‚Äôs pointless with AGI‚Äôs imminent arrival) to CEOs (who are deciding what projects to invest in, sometimes assuming AI will be more capable in 1-2 years than any likely reality).

The original Turing Test, which required a computer to fool a human judge, via text chat, into being unable to distinguish it from a human, has been insufficient to indicate human-level intelligence. The Loebner Prize competition actually ran the Turing Test and found that being able to simulate human typing errors ‚Äî perhaps even more than actually demonstrating intelligence ‚Äî was needed to fool judges. A main goal of AI development today is to build systems that can do economically useful work, not fool judges. Thus a modified test that measures ability to do work would be more useful than a test that measures the ability to fool humans.

For almost all AI benchmarks today (such as GPQA, AIME, SWE-bench, etc.), a test set is determined in advance. This means AI teams end up at least indirectly tuning their models to the published test sets. Further, any fixed test set measures only one narrow sliver of intelligence. In contrast, in the Turing Test, judges are free to ask any question to probe the model as they please. This lets a judge test how ‚Äúgeneral‚Äù the knowledge of the computer or human really is. Similarly, in the Turing-AGI Test, the judge can design any experience ‚Äî which is not revealed in advance to the AI (or human subject) being tested. This is a better way to measure generality of AI than a predetermined test set.

I‚Äôm going to say this once, and I don‚Äôt care if it makes people uncomfortable.

If you have never lived in Venezuela
If you did not grow up there
If you did not watch your country collapse in real time
If you did not stand in food lines
If you did not watch your parents lose everything they built
If you did not have to leave your home with nothing

Then shut the fuck up.

You do not have an opinion.
Your opinion does not matter.
And you don‚Äôt get to lecture anyone about what‚Äôs happening there.

I‚Äôm Venezuelan.
I lived there most of my life until my early twenties.
I watched my country go from a functioning democracy to full blown socialism right in front of my eyes.

This is not politics to me.
This is trauma.

Before socialism, Venezuela was not perfect, but it worked.
There was trade.
There was money coming in.
There was investment from the US.
There were jobs.
There was food.
There was medicine.

My family had five businesses.
We had our home
We had investments.
We had a future.

Then the government started nationalizing everything.
Private companies were taken.
Foreign investors were pushed out.
Imports were blocked.
Price controls destroyed production.
Corruption exploded.

And everything died.

Not slowly.
Violently.

People didn‚Äôt suddenly become poor because of ‚Äúcapitalism‚Äù or ‚Äúthe US‚Äù or whatever bullshit slogan people like to repeat online.

They became poor because socialism destroyed incentives, destroyed production, destroyed trust, and destroyed hope.

People today in Venezuela are not debating ideology.
They are trying to survive.

They are trying to find food.
Trying to find medication.
Trying to keep their families alive.

So when I see people in the West posting from comfortable homes, full fridges, stable currencies, and safe streets talking about ‚Äúimperialism‚Äù or ‚ÄúUS bad‚Äù or ‚ÄúTrump this or that‚Äù

No.
It‚Äôs not complicated.
You‚Äôre just ignorant.

China is not rebuilding Venezuela.
Russia is not rebuilding Venezuela.
Cartels are not rebuilding Venezuela.

They are stealing.
They are extracting.
They are draining what‚Äôs left.

If the US comes in and reinvests
If refineries get rebuilt
If infrastructure gets restored
If imports open back up
If food, water, and medicine become accessible again
If people can work and earn with dignity

Then yes.
Let them take all the oil they want.

Because at least something gets built instead of destroyed.

This is something to celebrate.
Not because it‚Äôs perfect.
But because for the first time in a long time, there is hope.

Hope that families can eat.
Hope that people don‚Äôt have to flee their country.
Hope that Venezuela can function again.

If you‚Äôve never lived through a country collapsing
If you‚Äôve never watched socialism destroy everything around you
If you‚Äôve never had to leave your home because staying meant starvation

Then again
Shut the fuck up.

This isn‚Äôt theory.
This isn‚Äôt politics.
This is lived experience.

By Stephen Subero

The Constitution has not been amended. It has been violated, and then quietly treated as if it changed.

Nowhere is this betrayal more dangerous than with the war power.

Article I is unambiguous: the power to declare war belongs to Congress, and to Congress alone. The framers placed it there deliberately. They had lived under a king who could take a nation to war by personal decree. They built a republic so no single person could do the same.

But they did not stop at text. They feared the instrument as much as the authority.

The founders viewed standing armies with profound suspicion, not because they doubted military necessity, but because they understood what a permanent armed force in the hands of a single executive would become: a tool of ambition, a means of war without deliberation, and eventually the private army of whoever held power. James Madison warned that standing armies were "dangerous to liberty." Elbridge Gerry declared that standing armies in peacetime are "the bane of liberty." The Anti-Federalists made opposition to permanent military forces a centerpiece of their critique.

The design was deliberate: Congress would control the purse and the power to declare war. The military would be called into being for specific purposes, then disbanded. No president would have a permanent force at his disposal, ready to deploy on his word alone.

That design has been abandoned.

The United States now maintains the largest standing military in its history, deployed across the globe, available at presidential command, and used repeatedly without congressional authorization. The founders' structural safeguard has been dismantled. The army they feared would become an instrument of executive will has become exactly that.

Yet over decades, presidents have initiated military action without congressional consent. Congress has watched and said nothing. Courts have refused to intervene. And from that collective failure, a dangerous fiction has emerged: that presidential war-making is now constitutional because it has gone unchallenged for so long.

That is not how constitutional law works. That is how constitutional law dies.

Article I powers cannot be waived by neglect. They can be altered only by amendment, by the explicit consent of the people, through the process the Constitution itself prescribes. Inaction does not transfer authority. Silence does not repeal text. Habit does not override law.

What has changed is not the Constitution. What has changed is our willingness to enforce it, and the cowardice of those whose duty it is to do so.

Repeated violations have been laundered into precedent. Tolerated breaches have been rebranded as authorization. Custom has been permitted to masquerade as legality. This is not evolution of law. It is dereliction. It is complicity. It is the quiet betrayal of an oath.

The claim that it would now be "unfair" to insist on congressional authorization, because presidents have acted unilaterally for decades, turns the Constitution on its head. The unfairness is not in enforcing the rule late. The unfairness is in permitting power to profit from its own lawlessness.

If neglect can rewrite the Constitution, then no amendment is ever needed. Power needs only patience. Limits disappear not by repeal, but by exhaustion, not by argument, but by attrition.

This is precisely what the framers feared.

James Madison warned that liberty is endangered not by dramatic seizure but by "gradual and silent encroachments," the slow migration of power from where the Constitution placed it to where ambition wants it. The war power has migrated. Not by amendment. Not by consent. By silence, by cowardice, by the failure of every institution charged with preventing exactly this.

Thomas Jefferson foresaw the destination. He called it "elective despotism": a government chosen by the people but no longer restrained by them. A president who commands a global military and deploys it without Congress is not a chief executive. He is an elected monarch exercising the very power the Constitution was written to forbid.

Benjamin Franklin offered the darkest warning of all. On the final day of the Constitutional Convention, he predicted the republic would be "well administred for a Course of Years" but would "end in Despotism as other Forms have done before it, when the People shall become so corrupted as to need Despotic Government, being incapable of any other."

Franklin did not warn against tyrants. He warned against us.

That is why constitutional ignorance is not innocent. In a republic, the people are the final check. If citizens do not read the Constitution, do not understand why powers were separated, do not grasp why ambition was made to counter ambition, they cannot recognize when those limits are breached. They become not the guardians of liberty but the instruments of its destruction. A Constitution unknown to the people is a Constitution easily discarded by their rulers.

The text still says what it has always said. The president cannot take the nation to war without the explicit consent of Congress. Not a word has changed.

What has changed is us.

A Congress that will not assert its power. Courts that will not enforce the limits. Citizens who do not know the document they claim to revere. And a political class that treats the Constitution as ornament, invoked for applause, ignored when inconvenient.

This is not constitutional evolution. It is constitutional rot, the slow decay of self-government by a people who no longer demand it.

Neglect is not consent.

It is surrender.
